{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_deeth_ver01/data/sn86076247/00332890487/1920113001/1250.xml":{"full_text":"11 H!-_U \u2014gjui'WF' I. -I\nMICKIE. THE PRINTER'S DEVIL,\nHe Puts Up a \"Safety First\u201d Notice\nKAt *Vi TU9 OJO HOOAMi WV3 'ao&rto \\J?'m i\nI A FV9C9 \\U -TUt PAFtn tUAT ^V*i UA& Y.9FY KAN r\nU \u00a9OAUO 'Vi NOOViN <2>9 U9<390Vi\u20182>\\9AJ& 9DU\\\nANN OF UtU J\nsfc\\U<a\u2014S9fc?)\n\nfikvxo vevasm&CR, -ovtrc Awi-t \\u\n7 -cov*awa>*te Ptv^a ,wo, <vu eovte.\n^Agvc. AMO gQU MOO \u00abAfr6EP\nCash, suoewa -<\\xKte)\nA VAtAU -m'V46 I\nI XO PSAYTT ACJXJT\nvtia\nNEXT\nDAY\n\nEORTUE SAKE\nOF DEAOE,\nMCVOE ROMS\nTHE\nKIOTVCE AVK>\nSEOO\\CETV\\\nTUAl WE \\S\nNOT ABOOT\n1b B\u00a3\n\"RUN RACKED*\n\u00abON, \\UWCvT VAtAVi fcN PS.\\VjTm6\n\u2022AN UV3S&MN0 NJOOVXT P<VN *AH fcWXS\u2014'WUN, LJ\n\\Nt 90990\u00abXSS> N\\WC USJLN UXK f^NWRS'U\nnoo ecrr\u00abj.\u00abj>A>Noo\nUTTLt vwu^reu,\nfcl\u00a3V=0&9. SV1KTX3A\nJSOU VMDV&*XS>\\1\nAsotvee\n\u2022fe -ro mmuuso wura\nJi;/ -awctvrrCut 6,U>N6\nHIRE A\nall!\nMuch Interest in the proposed Mc\nFadden gold bonus bill during th(\nrecent political campaign In Nevada\nThe statement of Congressman Louis\nT. McFadden. chairman of the bank\ning and currency committee of tht\nHouse of Representatives, presentee\nbefore the recent forty-sixth annuai\nconvention of the American Banking\nAssociation, held at Washington. D.C.\nis a sound and thoughtful discussion\nof fundamental monetary economics\nand remarks of the Kngineering and\nMining Journal relative thereto are\nQuoted for the benefit of interested\ncitizens of Nevada.\nConcerning the advisability of a\nbonus to gold miners, as proposed by\nMr. McFadden, bankers are by no\nmeans in agreement. There are two\nmutually dissenting parties, as there\nare outside the banking world. Mc\nFaddi n\u2019s argument is directed against\nthe report of a certain gold commit\ntee appointed by the American Bank\ning Association, which rendered an\nadverse report on the bill; but this\ncommittee is held by sponsors of the\nbill to represent a minority, and it is\ncertain that some important banking\ninterests remain so nuich In favor of\nthe bill that they have included a\nstatement of their support in their\nnewspaper advertisements.\nNow the proposition, if it is to\nstand, and if it should stand, must be\nshown to be desirable, first and last,\non the basis of national welfare.\nWhile the mining industry naturally\nhas its cause very much at heart, it\nwould be not only unfair but suicidal\nif any measure should be advocated\nby miners which, though it would res\ncue the gold-mining industry from\ndisaster, would depress the prosperity\nof the remainder of the country and\ndelay the natural healing process\nnecessary for the industrial wounds\nof war. It is on this broad basis of\nnational welfare, and no other, that\nthe measure is presented, and on\nwhich we support It, says the journal\nmentioned.\nThose bankers who oppose the bill\nare misled in some cases, it appears,\nby some elementary knowledge of\neconomics, proving anew that a little\nInum lofiffo iu a ilsitxrnrnna f liititr \\f r\nMcFadden, for example, combats the\nstatement of the gold committee that\n\"increased gold production in a period\nof low prices and low costs makes it\neasier for prices to rise again, while\ndiminished gold production in periods\nof high prices and costs tends to re\nduce prices and costs.\"\nHere, in a way, is a true and funda\nmental statement; and yet it is abso\nlutely Inapplicable to the present\ncase. It is evident that with gold, or\nsilver, or anything else, as a medium\nof exchange, the greater the supply\nof the standard the cheaper it will\nbecome, and the less it will purchase;\nin other words, the prices of other\ncommodities will rise in terms of gold\nor silver, as the case may be. This\nwas illustrated by the discovery of\nthe great Valenciana silver mine in\nMexico, in the sixteenth century. The\nflood of Bilvcr caused a rise of com\nmodity prices throughout the c.ivilized\nworld.\nThe absolute inapplicability of this\nlawr to the present world monetary\nconditions lies in the fact that our\nbasis of exchange is now not gold and\nsilver, but so-called money which is\nmostly paper with a minimum and\nquite insufficient security of gold\nand silver. Therefore it is now and\nlong will be the case that the mone\ntary control of prices (there are of\ncourse other factors) follows the law\nthat commodity prices will tend to\nIncrease as the ratio of paper to\nmetal (gold) increases; that they will\nrise with the inflation and diminish\nwith deflation. Deflation means a di\nminished ratio of paper to gold; and\nthere are two ways of accomplishing\nit\u2014one by decreasing the amount of\npaper, the other by increasing the\namount of gold. The latter is what\nthe McFadden bill proposes to do.\nA more astonishing economic view,\nurged by a great financier against\nthe McFadden bill, that it is inadvis\nable to increase the gold reserve, as\nthat would mean more credit based\nupon the increased gold, and so fur\nther credit, and so further inflation!\nIt is difficult to argue concerning this\nwarped point of view, as it assumes\nthe fundamental depravity of Ameri\ncan bankers- which may or may not\nbe true. Certainly, the financier who\nUttered this objection should know\n\u25a0'\u2022MMMHMHMaHHMMaBHIHnaHMi\n\u2018better than we; but, if so, the reme\ndial castigation should be applied tc\nour banking system. On this theory\ni the way to induce deflation would be\nby reducing the gold reserve, and\ncomplete deflation would be accom\nplished with its disappearance!\nj Though We are not threatened with\nany situation so extreme as the con\ndition of complete disappearance, ap\nparently viewed with equanimity by\nour great banker, we are face to face\nwith a shrinking gold reserve which\nwe can hardly escape. We can hard\nly expect stable return of prosperity\ntill Europe again becomes a buyer as\nlargely as of old. The present situa\ntion in copper is typical of this. Now,\nEurope cannot buy before her ex\nchange depreciation is remedied\nuntil then she has nothing to offer us.\nThe slowing down of her purchases,\nhowever, increases the amount of her\nexports as compared with her im\nports, and, as regards us, this means\nthat her balance of trade with us is\nbeing gradually adjusted, which\nmeans eventually a \"movement of our\ngold to Europe to adjust balances;\nand this is a tendency which will be\nhealthy for the world. Against this\nthe fact is that more gold is now go\ning Into the arts in this country\u2014\nprincipally jewelry\u2014than we are pro\nducing\u2014so that our outstanding pa\nper currency v^ill tend to have a\nshrinking basis of metal security.\nOur whole endeavor should be to\nbuild up the world\u2019s metal security\nunderlying its paper notes. The .Mc\nFadden bill could wisely be adopted\nI in this country, and copied in all\nother gold-producing countries. It\nserves the double purpose of tending\nto increase the production of gold\nand decrease the economic waste of\nit by turning it into purposes of\nadornment. The tax of approximate\nly 50 per cent which the jewelers\nwould have to pay is a moderate one.\nConsidering the general problem of\ntaxation for revenue, together with\nthe McFadden problem of taxation for\nincrease of gold reserve, we would\nbe inclined to recommend a 500 per\ncent tax on gold and jewelry, of\nwhich 50 per cent would be turned\nover to the miners as a bonus, and\nthe remainder into the treasury to\nhelp meet the general expenses of the\ngovernment.\nW think that the McFadden propo\n1 sition might well be modified so as to\n1 exempt from taxation gold employed\nfor useful purposes, as In dentistry.\nThis would further insure the retain\ning of the commodity standard of gold,\nj value as on the old fixed basis, and\nwould, in addition, refute the charge\nof a change in the gold standard.\nBut the hoarding of gold, especially\nin times of great financial stringency,\nis looked upon with disfavor by bank\ners; indeed, if the reader will ask for\na single $20 gold piece from his bank\nhe probably will detect some disfavor\nor suspicion on the part of the bank\ner; and it is nothing less than board-,\ning to suspend it around one's neck\nor across one\u2019s chest, or locked up in\none\u2019s strong box as jewelry. Hoard\ning of this sort of silver and gold (as\nornaments) in India has long made\nthat country a veritable sink of the\nmetals; and at the present time more\nthan the total production of the coun\n1 try in gold is thus hoarded in this\ncountry as jewelry. Will not the\nbankers view this also with the ap\npropriate alarm?\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC LAND IS\nPASSING TO INDIVIDUAL HANDS\nIt may not be generally known that\nChurchill county lands are Tjelng\ngrabbed up at a pretty lively rate thi.^\nyear, says the Kagle, but a glance at\nthe assessment roll shows conclu\nsively that many of our home people,\nas well as those from other states,\nhave been investing in railroad land3.\nFrom the first of the year to Septem\nber, when an order came to withdraw\nall railroad lands from sale, more\nthan 37,000 acres had been sold, and\nthere were in this 112 purchasers,\nthe greater number of whom bought\nin forty and eightv-acre tracts. All\nof this land, with the possible excep\nt'on of two or three sections, lies\nwithin the Newlands project, being\nnorth and west of Fallon, including\nconsiderable in the Sheckler district\nand the Hazen section.\nAmong the purchasers are a great\ntany people from Idaho. Nearly all\nof this land was purchased under the\nusual Southern Pacific, contract sys\ntem, but It means the passing from\nthe railroad into the hunds of Indi\nviduals and the improving of the land\no a greater or less extent.\nS ve time- therefore money. Use\nwunUd column. 3 times, 30 cents.\nWomen voters have expressed sc\nmuch interest in the personality ol\nAlice Robertson, the woman who wat\nelected to Congress from Oklahoma\nthat the following recent letter from\nher home town is reproduced for the\nbenefit of readers in Nevada where\na woman wasn\u2019t elected:\nFor most ordinary mortals the run\nning of a big cafeteria or the manage\nment of a successful modern farm\nwould require all one's time and\nenergy; but for -Miss Alice Robertson,\nCongresswoman-elect and person of\ndiverse talents, the two are but a part\nof the many and varied activities in\nwhich she has entered with all her\nacumen and pep.\nThis does not mean that the farm\nis not well kept or that the cafeteria\nis not up to date, for both are just\nthis, and in the widest sense. With\nthe products of her farm she has\nwon many prizes and awards at the\nfairs, while there are a few in Mus\nkogee who will not award her eating\nplace first prize in cleanliness, qual\nity and atmosphere.\nMiss Robertson has not only made\nher cafeteria successful from the\nfinancial standpoint, but she has\ntiade it a gathering place for Mus\nkogeeans of every class and char\nacter. The cafeteria is used for many\nlodge gatherings of one kind or an\nother, particularly by the American\nLegion and other service men's or\nganizations.\nDuring the campaign that preceded\nher election it was her political head\nquarters, and that meant for the en\ntire Republican party.\nAfter election the cafeteria became\nmore popular than ever before, for\nmany came there out of curiosity to\nsee the latest congresswoman.\nBoth the farm and cafeteria ar\nnamed Sawokla, from the Indian\nword meaning \"always welcome.\u201d\nAnd Miss Alice makes everyone feel\nat home at both places, for she is\na real southern hostess, when it\ncomes to hospitality and friendliness.\nStirring around among her patrons\nat the cafeteria. Miss Robertson has\na welcome for all. Moat Mus\nkogeeans know her to talk to, and\nj everyone knows her by sight.\nMany votes were won and lost over\nthe soup or pie. Although Miss Rob\nertson rarely talked politics, she did\ngain many a vote by her casual wel\nconies.\nThe cafeteria was started as a\nworking girls* lunch room in April,\n1913. It grew and grew through half\na dozen different locations until it\nI reached its present quarters, last\nj May. Only last spring it was in a\nj basement in a big office building,\nj The farm got its start while Alice\nwas yet a postmaster. She bought\nmost of the land in 1907. It comprises\n54 acres, part of which is in the city\nlimits. Practically ail of it overlooks\nthe city from the heights that have\nbeen dedicated as a city park to those\nwho fought in France.\nPure bred cattle and hogs are in\nevidence at the farm. Miss Robert\nson is right at home in every depart\nI ment. Though she leaves the actual\nwork to others, she knows everything\n,that goes on. She has Duroc-Jersey\nhogs and Jersey cattle.\nMost of the produce she uses at\nthe cafeteria comes from her farm.\nVegetables, fruits, meats, and many\nother products come dirpfct without\nany middleman's profits added.\nHer farm exhibit has taken first\nprize at the Oklahoma free state fair\nfor several years. While her 1920\nexhibit was not up to former years,\nit contained 40 varieties of fruits and\nvegetables in cans and jars.\nHIGH TEMPER.4TI RE IX OFFICE\nSI RPRISE TO COMMISSIONERS j\nWhen members of the state board i\nof parole commissioners assembled i\nin the Governor's office Tuesday after-\nnoon the temperature in the room was\nso high (about 110 degrees) that win\ndows were opened and radiators shut\noff before the business of the day\nwas taken up. says the Carson City\nNews. j\nA conference between the Gov- i\nj ernor and a delegation of Gold Hill j\ntnipers had been held in the office\nearlier in the day and it was jok-\ningly declared that an effort had been j\nmade to have conditions such that\nthe \"hot water plugs\u2019\u2019 would feel per\nfectly at ease.\nThe Silver State\u201450 cents the month\nRed Crown\nGasoline is\nan all-refinery\ngasoline with\na continuous\nchain of boiling\npoints.\nSTANDARD OIL CO.\n(California)\ny,e\n\n\n44444444444>444444444\n4 4\nDK, A. A. WENDELL 4\nDentist 4\nGraduate of the Chicago College 4\nof Dental Surgery, class of 1891 41\nFirst National Bank Building I\n4\n4444444444<f>444444444;\n44444444444444444444\n4 4\n4 DK. M. E. MORRISON 4\n4 Dentist\n4 X-Kay Laboratory 4\nOffice: Huston-Grandin Building <8*\n4 Phones: Office 724, residence 793 4\n4\n44444444444444444444\n44444444444444 44 4444\n4\nDR. F. A. NEILSON 4\n4 Dentist 4\nHours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. 4\n316 Bridge Street 4\n4 Winnemucca, Nevada 4\n4 4\n444 4 44 4 4 4 4 4 4'44 4 4 4444\n4 4 4' S' 4 s- 4 4 4 4 4' 4 4 4 4 S\u2019 4 4 4 4\n4 4'\n<s> DK. W. T. LIGGETT 4\n\u2022s\u2019 Physician and Surgeon 4\ns\u2019 Office over First National Bank 4\nPhone 892 4\nWinnemucca, Nevada 4\n4 4\n44444444444444444444\n44444444444444444444\n4 4\n4 DR. G. T. HALL 4\n4 Physician and Surgeon 4\n4 Office and residence: E. Third St. 4\n4 Hours: 11 to 4; 7 to 9. Phone 1972 4\n4 'Winnemucca, Nevada 4\nA 4\n44444444444444444444\n44 4 4 4<\u2022>44 44 4444 444444\n4 4\n4 H. H. SHELDON 4\n4 Civil Engineer 4\n4 IT. S. Mineral Suveyor 4\n4 Office: Bridge St., near Fourth 4\n4 Winnemucca, Nevada 4\n4 4\n44444444 444444 4 44444\n44444444444444444444\n4 4\n4 J. A. LANGWITH 4\n4 Attorney-at-Laiv i\n4 Bridge Street, near Fourth 4\n4 Phone 304 4\n4 Winnemucca, Nevada 4\n4 4\n44444444444444444444\nZ 'y 'Z 'V '\u2022zJ V5' W '\u2022y y y\n<J>\nCAMPBELL ROBINS\nAttorneys, at-Law\nOffices: Wrnneva Building\nBridge Street\ns\u2019 Winnemucca, Nevada\n<J>\n<S> V\n\u2018$<$><S> W\nS>\nL. G. W ILSON\nAttorney\nand <3>\nCounselor-at-Law j\n3> Winnemucca, Nevada <s>\nS> <S>\n<S> <^<$><S> <8> i\nWINNEMUCCA -AERIE No. 487, F.O.E.\nRegular meetings on fourth Mon\nday evening of each month in Win\nneva Hail. .Visiting Eagles are\ncordially invited to attend ail\nsessions. I\nW. H. AYRES, W.P. I\nGEORGE WESCOATT. Secretary.\n=n\nCarlson Co.\nFUNERAL DIRECTORS\nEast